The '''Chicago Milk Commission''' (CMC) was formed in 1908 to combat the consumption of unpasteurized milk which was regarded as a leading cause of infant death in the Chicago area.<ref name="Pegram">{{cite book|author=Pegram, Thomas R.|title=Partisans and Progressives: Private Interest and Public Policy in Illinois, 1870-1922|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IzeikFNF4RAC&pg=PA56|year=1992|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana & Chicago|isbn=978-0-252-01847-3|page=56}}</ref> It established "milk stations" throughout the city, which provided free pasteurized milk. The staff and volunteers of the CMC created the [[Infant Welfare Society of Chicago]] in 1911.<ref>[https://infantwelfaresociety.org/our-history/ Our History.] Infant Welfare Society of Chicago. Retrieved 18 August 2018.</ref>
In 1916 the [[Milk Producers Association]] started a series of milk strikes, to increase the price paid by Chicago dealers. By 1917 the rising price of milk lead to much reduced consumption (25% that year alone) causing concerns about child welfare. The CMC set the price to 13 cents per quart, for home delivery, a cent less than the prevailing price.<ref name="Pegram 1992">{{Cite book|author=Thomas R. Pegram|title=Partisans and Progressives: Private Interest and Public Policy in Illinois, 1870-1922|date=1 April 1992|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-01847-3|pages=59}}</ref>
